Title:
Enumerating Windows Process Creation Callbacks

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4â€“8 sentences max):
- This post explains how Windows tracks kernel-mode process creation notification callbacks via the `PspCreateProcessNotifyRoutine` array and demonstrates enumerating those callbacks from user mode.  
- It solves the problem of identifying which security/EDR drivers are registered to receive process creation events (i.e., who â€śseesâ€ť new processes immediately).  
- The technique uses `NtQuerySystemInformation(SystemModuleInformation)` to map loaded kernel modules, then leverages a BYOVD vulnerable driver exposing an arbitrary kernel read primitive to read and walk the 64-entry callback array.  
- It covers decoding the stored callback pointers (masking flag bits), dereferencing the `EX_CALLBACK` structure to recover the real function pointer, and attributing each callback to a driver by address range matching.  
- A Windows 11 PoC output shows callbacks attributed to drivers like `WdFilter.sys` (Defender) and other core components.  
- The post also discusses detection realities (often the vulnerable driver is detected, not the enumeration logic) and provides a sample YARA rule to flag binaries implementing this enumeration pattern.  
- Useful for red teams/malware devs doing EDR recon/evasion research and for blue teams building detections around BYOVD + kernel callback enumeration behavior.

Technical Focus:
- `PspCreateProcessNotifyRoutine` process creation notify callbacks
- BYOVD kernel read primitives via `DeviceIoControl` IOCTLs
- `NtQuerySystemInformation` / `SystemModuleInformation` kernel module enumeration
- Pointer decoding / flag-bit masking and `EX_CALLBACK` dereference
- Callback-to-driver attribution via module base/size range checks
- YARA-based static detection patterns for callback enumeration tooling

Use Cases:
- Enumerate which EDR/security drivers monitor process creation on a host
- Kernel telemetry reconnaissance prior to process injection/spawn-heavy tradecraft
- Validate whether a driver successfully registered process notify callbacks
- Build detections/hunts for BYOVD-assisted kernel memory inspection activity
- Research Windows kernel callback internals and common EDR monitoring points

Keywords:
Windows kernel, PspCreateProcessNotifyRoutine, process creation callbacks, PsSetCreateProcessNotifyRoutine, EX_CALLBACK, ntoskrnl.exe, NtQuerySystemInformation, SystemModuleInformation, BYOVD, vulnerable driver, arbitrary kernel read, DeviceIoControl, IOCTL, GIO, GDRV, WdFilter.sys, EDR telemetry, kernel memory enumeration, YARA rule, Windows 11